@startuml
title Proximity Crafting - Runtime Request / Response Flow
skinparam shadowing false

actor User
participant "Screen or overlay\n(Forge/Fabric/NeoForge)" as Ui
participant "Shared screen runtime\ncontroller(s)" as RuntimeController
participant "ClientRequestSender" as Sender
participant "Platform packet transport" as Transport
participant "Menu / session host" as MenuHost
participant "Common operations" as CommonOps
participant "Platform S2C handler" as S2CHandler
participant "ClientResponseDispatcher" as Dispatcher
participant "ClientRecipeSessionState" as SessionState
participant "ActiveClientSessionHandle" as SessionHandle
participant "Screen UI update" as UiUpdate

User -> Ui : click / scroll / clear / recipe fill
Ui -> RuntimeController : enqueue / normalize / schedule
RuntimeController -> Sender : send outbound request
Sender -> Transport : C2S packet
Transport -> MenuHost : route to open runtime session
MenuHost -> CommonOps : execute fill / adjust / clear / consume
CommonOps --> MenuHost : result + updated state
MenuHost -> Transport : S2CRecipeBookSourceSnapshot\nand/or S2CRecipeFillFeedback
Transport -> S2CHandler : decode payload
S2CHandler -> Dispatcher : handleRecipeBookSourceSnapshot(...)\nhandleRecipeFillFeedback(...)
Dispatcher -> SessionHandle : resolve active session by containerId
Dispatcher -> SessionState : apply source snapshot / feedback state
Dispatcher -> SessionHandle : replace sources / run UI-side hooks
SessionHandle -> RuntimeController : runtime-neutral outcomes
RuntimeController -> UiUpdate : request panel, status, recipe book,\ncompat follow-up hooks
UiUpdate --> User : updated visible state

note right of Transport
Current S2C payloads:
- RecipeBookSourceSnapshotPayload
- RecipeFillFeedbackPayload
end note

note bottom
Transport and packet registration remain platform-side.
Request/response intent, state application, and session coordination
now live behind shared common seams, with screen runtime behavior
coordinated before dispatch and after response handling.
end note
@enduml
